 estate’, or from Pennington in Leigh (Lancashire), which probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Pinna</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","habitational name from Pennington (Hampshire), or from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hampshire); see   Penton  . All have the same etymology as Pennington in Furness; see 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Penington","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Pennington  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland.","History: Edward Penington, born in 1667 in Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England, was appointed surveyor-general of the province of PA in 1698 and accompanied William Penn to Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Penton","meanings":["English (mainly Hampshire):","habitational name from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hanmpshire), or from a shortened form of   Pennington   2. The placenames denoted a farm or estate for which a penny tax was payable (Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i>).","in north-west England, a shortened form of   Pennington   1, from either of the places called Pennington in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Pennington was born in 1275, in Heversham, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom as the son of John de Pennington I. He had at least 1 son with Mother Pennington. He died in 1323, in Pennington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1275–1323":"1275–1323","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1300–1368":"1300–1368","1294–Male":"1294–Surnud","1233–1277":"1233–1277","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1233":"1233","1275":"1275","20 Sep 1277":"20. september 1277","1294":"1294","Muncaster Castle, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Pennington, Lancashire, England":"Pennington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","richard, heversham, westmoreland, England":"Heversham, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1275–1323":"1275–1323","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1300–1368":"1300–1368","1294–Male":"1294–Kuollut","1233–1277":"1233–1277","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1233":"1233","1275":"1275","20 Sep 1277":"20. syyskuuta 1277","1294":"1294","Muncaster Castle, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Pennington, Lancashire, England":"Pennington, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","richard, heversham, westmoreland, England":"Heversham, Westmorland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1275–1323":"1275–1323","1275–Female":"1275–Décédée","1300–1368":"1300–1368","1294–Male":"1294–Décédé","1233–1277":"1233–1277","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1233":"1233","1275":"1275","20 Sep 1277":"20 septembre 1277","1294":"1294","Muncaster Castle, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre","Pennington, Lancashire, England":"Pennington, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","richard, heversham, westmoreland, England":"Heversham, Westmorland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Pennington est né en 1275, à Heversham, Westmorland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de John de Pennington I. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mother Pennington. Il est décédé en 1323, à Pennington, La